TUCSON-For the first time a
Negro was elected to head a
Knights of Columbus 4th degree
In Arizona.


James Aikens was named faith.
full navigator of the Archbishop
Daniel Cercke General Assembly
4th Degree Knights Of Columbus
last week.


He previously held every chair
position in this degree which is
the honorary and highest degree
in the Knights of Columbus.


The Knights of Columbus Is an
American organization of Roman
Catholic men.

Negro Gets High
K Of { Chair

Judge Laurens L. Henderson
will seek reelection to the Super
for Court in the Republican pri-
mary Sept. 9th.


Presently presiding in Division
9. Judge Henderson was named
to activate the new Court ofCon-
ciliation in Maricopa County
which is being established to re-
concile married couples, partic-
ularly those having children.


He was appointed to the bench
in 1859 by Gov. Paul Fannin and
he was elected to a four year
term in 1860.


A graduate of Dartmouth, Judge
Henderson has practiced law
from 1925 until being appointed
to the bench. He has lived In
Arizona since 1898.

Judge Hend erson


Seeks Seat Again

WASHINGTON-Minnie Harris
field, a member of the Veterans
Administration Nursing Ser
vice since 1889, has been ap-
pointed psychiatric nursing spec
ialist for the Nursing Appraisal
and Program Development Dr.
vision here.


She is the first Negro nurse
to be named to a top position
on the central office staff Of
director of nursing Cecilia H.
Hauge.


A graduate of Tuskegee Insti-
tute, Mrs. Hartsfield received
her masters degree in nursing
education at Columbia Univer-
sity.


She was associated with the
VAS research program in Chi
cago before accepting this posi-
ton on July l. Previously she
had been at the Danville, ILL
nois; Salisbury, North Carolina;
Downey. Illinois; and Tuskegee
VA Hospitals.

Within an hour we we're heading
east on Broadway. Home never
looked so great. like to roam
like to go--but | will let you know
there's just no place like homel


didn't leave my heart in San
Francisco---instead left my
smog red eyes. My husband
returns there Sunday for the
National Republican Convention.
| know the city has changed with
so many people there for the COP
affair. I'll return another time.
perhaps next spring.

Miss Jacqueline Frances Smith
will marry DR.. Rowell S. Ash
ford August 7 at Southminster
Presbyterian Church. 1923 E.
Broadway Rd.


Miss Smith attended Trinity
University, San Antonio. Texas
for two years and she received
her bachelors degree from Ari-
IONA State University this June.
She majored in education.


She was affiliated with Or
chests Dance honorary society,
Gee and Kappa Delta Pi.


Her parents are Mr.. and Mrs.
]. Ford Smith, 5025 So. 21st
Way.


Her fiance attended Fisk Uni
versiy and received his medical
degree from Meharry Medical
College in Nashville, Tenn.


He is presently a captain in
the USAF, stationed at Luke Air
Force Base.


His parents are MIR. and Mrs.
Thomas Ashford, of Birmingham.

JoEtta Griffin, II, daughter
of Mrs. Cora McCline and Jo-
seph P. Griffin. received the
Phoenix Links scholarship to the
All State High School Music
Camp. She attended sessions at
Arizona State University.


JoEtta is studying voice and she
had classes in ballet, choral
group singing and ceramics.


She completed her junior year
in high school and she spends
much Of her time singing as a
member of two choirs, the Phoe-
nix Union High School A Capella
and Tanner AME Church youth
choir.
